Although the risk characteristics of this portfolio will be similar to that displayed above, returns will not necessarily correlate with the selected strategy. While allocations to multiple asset classes can reduce risk, risk of loss cannot be completely eliminated with diversification. There is no guarantee that the identified mix of asset classes will eliminate risk, reduce your current exposure to risk, or manage your exposure to risk in a way that is tolerable for you. All displayed portfolios are subject to Bond Risk, Liquidity Risk, Market Price Risk, Market Risk, Non-US Risk and High Yield Risk.

Bond Risk – Bonds are subject to interest rate risk. As the prevailing level of bond interest rates rise, the value of bonds already held in a portfolio decline. Portfolios that hold bonds are subject to declines and increases in value due to general changes in interest rates.

Liquidity Risk – ETF trading may be halted due to market conditions, impacting an investor’s ability to sell a fund.

Market Price Risk – The market price of ETF traded on the secondary market is subject to the forces of supply and demand and thus independent of the NAV. This can result in the market price trading at a premium or discount to the NAV which will affect an investor’s value.

Market Risk – The market prices of ETF’s can fluctuate as a result of several factors, such as security-specific factors or general investor sentiment. Therefore, investors should be aware of the prospect of market fluctuations and the impact it may have on the market price.

Non-US Risk – Securities of companies located outside the US are subject to additional risks such as political instability, exchange rate risk - since you are investing dollars and their earnings are in another currency, and liquidity risk – since some foreign stock and bond markets are not as efficient as US markets.

High-Yield Risk – High Yield bonds have lower ratings than investment grade bonds, typically BB and lower. Rating agencies believe they are more likely to default than bonds with higher ratings.
